definitions.definition: To order , give orders ; to compel or direct with authority.
examples: The soldier was commanded to cease firing.
The king commanded his servant to bring him dinner.

definitions.definition: To have or exercise supreme power, control or authority over, especially military; to have under direction or control.
To require with authority; to demand , order , enjoin .
to dominate through ability, resources, position etc.; to overlook .
To exact , compel or secure by influence; to deserve , claim .
examples: A good magistrate commands the respect and affections of the people.
Justice commands the respect and affections of the people.
The best goods command the best price.
This job commands a salary of £30,000.

definitions.definition: To hold , to control the use of.
To have a view (of), as from a superior position.
To direct to come; to bestow .
